      "content": "No worries, I'll stick to the math.\n\nA p-value of 0.04 in a clinical trial for blood pressure meds means that if there is no real effect of the medication on blood pressure (i.e., the null hypothesis is true), the probability of observing the results you got (or more extreme) is 4%. This is a relatively low probability, which suggests that the observed effect is unlikely to be due to chance.\n\nIn this context, a p-value of 0.04 is generally considered statistically significant, which means that the null hypothesis can be rejected. This implies that there is a statistically significant difference in blood pressure between the treatment group (taking the medication) and the control group (not taking the medication).\n\nHowever, it's essential to consider the context of the study, including the sample size, the type of analysis used, and the clinical significance of the observed effect. A p-value of 0.04 might not be practically significant, meaning that the effect size is small or not clinically meaningful.\n\nTo give you a better idea, a p-value of 0.04 is roughly equivalent to saying that if you were to repeat the study 100 times, you would expect to see a statistically significant result (i.e",
